    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1968-08-15T20:15:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1968-08-15T20:15:00-05:00" n="217"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d217">
                <head>217. Telegram From the <gloss type="from">Embassy in the Dominican
                        Republic</gloss> to the <gloss type="to">Department of State</gloss>
                    <note n="1" type="source" xml:id="d217fn1">Source: National Archives and Records
                        Administration, RG 59, Central Files 1967–69, POL 2 DOM</note>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>Santo Domingo</placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian"
                            when="1968-08-16T01:15:00+00:00">August 16, 1968,
                        0115Z</date>.</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>3410. Subject: Current Political Problems Facing <persName corresp="#p_BJ1"
                        >Balaguer</persName> Government.</p>
                <pb facs="0568" n="533" xml:id="pg_533"/>
                <p>
                    <hi rend="italic">1. Summary</hi>
                </p>
                <p>Review current political mood and governmentʼs handling of problem areas since
                    municipal elections opportune as August 16 approaches, day on which municipal
                    governments throughout country are renewed or change over. Array of problems
                    facing <persName corresp="#p_BJ1">Balaguer</persName> government is formidable
                    but in many instances represents chronic problems or variations of chronic
                    problems. Principal ones include: (a) charges of lack “democratic” atmosphere
                    within which opposition can function, prompted in particular by closing <gloss
                        target="#t_PRD1">PRD</gloss> radio program; (b) hunger strike self-styled
                    political prisoners; (c) acts terrorism and alleged police repression and
                    excesses; (d) recent attempts largely by Haitians seek political asylum
                    Venezuelan and Chilean embassies; (e) reports of new rumblings in armed forces;
                    (f) reports of planning for violence in connection change-over national district
                    government. <persName corresp="#p_BJ1">Balaguer</persName> in past has been able
                    through combination factors handle or control similar problems and has projected
                    image of man in charge. Now, however, and especially since May elections,
                    President has become more passive and defensive in face opposition actions.
                    Consequence is accumulation of problems and lack of tone in government. Our
                    judgement, however, is that no acute crisis looming; but we are concerned that
                    gradual downhill slide will continue if <persName corresp="#p_BJ1"
                        >Balaguer</persName> does not reassume direction firmly. It would be in this
                    context that government would become increasingly vulnerable to initiatives on
                    part opposition or unforeseen events.</p>
                <p>[Omitted here is the remainder of the telegram detailing the points raised in the
                    summary.]</p>
            </div>
